1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,000
https://slama.dev/comeback/

2
00:00:11,850 --> 00:00:14,910
Marcelka, you got a package.

3
00:00:16,050 --> 00:00:18,550
Those must be the ear candles I ordered.

4
00:00:18,660 --> 00:00:19,580
Ear candles?

5
00:00:19,640 --> 00:00:21,600
It's disgusting to make candles from ears.

6
00:00:21,760 --> 00:00:23,540
They're not candles from ears, but for ears.

7
00:00:23,680 --> 00:00:25,580
To me it looks more like something you smoke.

8
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:27,800
It's a Chinese health aid.

9
00:00:28,020 --> 00:00:28,800
What's it for?

10
00:00:29,450 --> 00:00:30,340
It's obvious, isn't it?

11
00:00:30,650 --> 00:00:31,850
So it's not dark in your ears.

12
00:00:32,850 --> 00:00:34,980
It improves circulation and cleans the sinuses.

13
00:00:36,450 --> 00:00:39,750
You just stick it in your ear like this and light it here.

14
00:00:39,840 --> 00:00:41,080
And you inhale here.

15
00:00:43,400 --> 00:00:44,560
That was a joke.

16
00:00:45,360 --> 00:00:46,860
I think you inhale through the nose.

17
00:00:49,100 --> 00:00:49,580
Hey.

18
00:00:50,350 --> 00:00:51,340
What are you doing here?

19
00:00:51,340 --> 00:00:52,400
No school or what?

20
00:00:52,600 --> 00:00:53,700
We got the day off.

21
00:00:54,050 --> 00:00:57,360
They took Benes to the hospital with suspected African disease.

22
00:00:57,360 --> 00:00:57,840
What?

23
00:00:58,120 --> 00:00:59,540
Yeah, they took him right from class.

24
00:00:59,720 --> 00:01:00,820
How did he catch it?

25
00:01:01,650 --> 00:01:04,040
He was in Tunisia with his parents and a camel spat on him.

26
00:01:04,040 --> 00:01:04,520
I see.

27
00:01:05,160 --> 00:01:07,560
And then they washed him with water at the hotel and that's probably how he got it.

28
00:01:09,120 --> 00:01:10,900
Now they're testing him for Nigerian dysentery.

29
00:01:11,650 --> 00:01:13,150
And we get a day off.

30
00:01:13,150 --> 00:01:16,640
Obviously, for these exotic diseases you need a radical solution.

31
00:01:16,950 --> 00:01:19,850
Like back in '73, remember, when we had the plague at school?

32
00:01:20,550 --> 00:01:21,780
Bro, what plague?

33
00:01:21,950 --> 00:01:24,240
In '73 your school burned down.

34
00:01:24,240 --> 00:01:25,880
That's what I'm saying, radical solution.

35
00:01:26,040 --> 00:01:28,140
If I hadn't set it on fire, we'd all be dead today.

36
00:01:29,600 --> 00:01:31,080
You set it on fire?

37
00:01:31,360 --> 00:01:32,220
What was I supposed to do?

38
00:01:32,950 --> 00:01:37,750
I'm sleeping peacefully in class and suddenly I hear the teacher say a great plague epidemic has broken out.

39
00:01:38,250 --> 00:01:40,450
Wasn't that in history class by any chance?

40
00:01:41,950 --> 00:01:43,150
What's that got to do with it?

41
00:01:44,260 --> 00:01:45,720
I'll go pack then.

42
00:01:45,720 --> 00:01:47,820
My God, you don't have to go to the hospital too?

43
00:01:47,820 --> 00:01:50,160
No, we're going to Horakova's cabin with the class.

44
00:01:50,220 --> 00:01:52,180
Since we have three days off now, if that's okay.

45
00:01:52,750 --> 00:01:53,980
The twins are already packing.

46
00:01:53,980 --> 00:01:58,580
Alright, as long as nobody protects you there by burning the whole place down...

47
00:01:58,580 --> 00:01:59,140
Don't worry.

48
00:01:59,260 --> 00:02:03,040
Since last year, Lexa has to surrender sharp objects and matches right on arrival.

49
00:02:05,440 --> 00:02:34,870
What's that?

50
00:02:36,170 --> 00:02:36,690
A swimsuit.

51
00:02:37,450 --> 00:02:37,890
Where?

52
00:02:39,550 --> 00:02:42,050
Dad, stop it, we live in the twenty-first century.

53
00:02:42,110 --> 00:02:45,950
Why don't you take those nice green one-piece ones I bought you for Croatia?

54
00:02:46,110 --> 00:02:48,770
You bought them five years ago, I was eleven.

55
00:02:48,990 --> 00:02:52,390
Still better than this nothing on a string, you might as well swim naked.

56
00:02:52,470 --> 00:02:53,210
And I could.

57
00:02:54,010 --> 00:02:55,270
Kropackova and Hajek do it too.

58
00:02:55,270 --> 00:03:00,130
Don't you dare parade around naked in front of a herd of germ carriers.

59
00:03:00,130 --> 00:03:00,570
Don't be dramatic.

60
00:03:01,890 --> 00:03:02,330
I'm not being dramatic?

61
00:03:02,470 --> 00:03:02,870
I'm reading.

62
00:03:04,350 --> 00:03:12,250
Salmonella nigeris, also known as Nigerian dysentery, is among the particularly dangerous diseases of African countries.

63
00:03:13,250 --> 00:03:16,430
For God's sake, don't start reading me the family doctor guide again.

64
00:03:16,430 --> 00:03:17,050
Of course not.

65
00:03:17,130 --> 00:03:19,070
This is an encyclopedia of exotic diseases.

66
00:03:19,270 --> 00:03:20,350
Where'd you get it?

67
00:03:21,350 --> 00:03:26,290
I bought it for you, so you'd recognize it if he caught dysentery somewhere.

68
00:03:26,650 --> 00:03:28,070
But listen.

69
00:03:28,550 --> 00:03:33,750
Among the first symptoms are sudden and intense diarrhea.

70
00:03:46,550 --> 00:03:52,350
Diarrhea causes dehydration, which manifests as burning thirst.

71
00:03:53,950 --> 00:03:56,860
Iva, which glass is this today?

72
00:03:56,860 --> 00:03:57,500
First.

73
00:03:58,470 --> 00:04:00,010
But it's almost empty.

74
00:04:00,010 --> 00:04:03,150
You're not dehydrated, Dad, that looks different.

75
00:04:19,250 --> 00:04:23,150
Another symptom is significant spatial disorientation.

76
00:04:30,850 --> 00:04:33,050
Iva, is it on the tip?

77
00:04:33,650 --> 00:04:34,150
Yeah, right on the tip.

78
00:04:34,450 --> 00:04:37,350
Look carefully, I feel like it's slightly to the left.

79
00:04:37,350 --> 00:04:37,930
Dad.

80
00:04:38,850 --> 00:04:43,350
Missing by two millimeters doesn't mean you have significant spatial disorientation.

81
00:04:44,350 --> 00:04:49,150
And how do you imagine significant spatial disorientation should look?

82
00:04:54,750 --> 00:04:55,950
Ozzak, what's wrong with you?

83
00:04:56,450 --> 00:04:59,450
Were you at the pub again, that you can't walk through a door?

84
00:05:00,250 --> 00:05:01,150
I'm not going anywhere.

85
00:05:01,750 --> 00:05:03,110
I'm jamming to the music.

86
00:05:03,550 --> 00:05:04,450
Nothing's playing right now.

87
00:05:04,550 --> 00:05:05,750
You can't hear anything?

88
00:05:07,750 --> 00:05:09,110
Indeed I can't hear anything.

89
00:05:09,170 --> 00:05:10,090
Doesn't that seem strange to you?

90
00:05:10,550 --> 00:05:13,190
Look, if you're so smart, go check the back yourself.

91
00:05:13,190 --> 00:05:14,150
I'm going back to the counter.

92
00:05:27,650 --> 00:05:31,450
In the final stages, dehydration causes babbling.

93
00:05:33,150 --> 00:05:35,570
Don't you think I've been saying anything nonsensical today?

94
00:05:35,750 --> 00:05:37,050
Yeah, that stuff about the swimsuit.

95
00:05:38,550 --> 00:05:43,850
Iva, I'm your father and as a father I have to make sure you don't put yourself on display.

96
00:05:44,350 --> 00:05:45,550
You're babbling again.

97
00:05:45,990 --> 00:05:46,510
Babbling?

98
00:05:48,250 --> 00:05:49,110
You really think so?

99
00:05:49,450 --> 00:05:50,750
No more than usual.

100
00:05:52,710 --> 00:05:53,230
Marcelka.

101
00:05:54,150 --> 00:05:58,550
This cream that gentleman wanted, should I wipe it up or wait for the war of the cats?

102
00:05:59,550 --> 00:06:00,070
Excuse me?

103
00:06:00,350 --> 00:06:02,750
Russians have deer and deer hatch watering cans.

104
00:06:04,150 --> 00:06:07,210
Ozzak, you're talking complete nonsense.

105
00:06:07,210 --> 00:06:08,730
You're drilling bread, boss.

106
00:06:10,750 --> 00:06:14,350
Market, celery, plasticine.

107
00:06:19,550 --> 00:06:21,640
Ozzak, you're behaving abnormally.

108
00:06:21,640 --> 00:06:24,850
I don't mean abnormally as in normally.

109
00:06:24,850 --> 00:06:28,050
I mean abnormally compared to your normal.

110
00:06:28,920 --> 00:06:30,020
Woman, what are you babbling about?

111
00:06:31,440 --> 00:06:34,040
Ozzak, maybe you should see a doctor.

112
00:06:34,160 --> 00:06:36,260
I know an excellent specialist in Bohnice.

113
00:06:36,260 --> 00:06:36,700
Enough, bimbo!

114
00:06:37,340 --> 00:06:38,340
Doctors are frauds.

115
00:06:39,050 --> 00:06:40,880
No illness can take down a real man.

116
00:06:40,880 --> 00:06:43,040
Maybe you don't even realize you're sick.

117
00:06:43,480 --> 00:06:46,000
There's no illness that half a liter of Fernet can't cure.

118
00:06:46,580 --> 00:06:48,960
My leg hurts, I have a Fernet, all good.

119
00:06:49,420 --> 00:06:52,080
My head hurts, I have a Fernet, all good again.

120
00:06:52,220 --> 00:06:54,600
My liver hurts, so I skip it.

121
00:06:54,980 --> 00:06:55,920
Fernet cures everything.

122
00:06:56,730 --> 00:06:58,690
Ozzak, there's really something wrong with you.

123
00:06:58,790 --> 00:07:00,070
You're all out of breath.

124
00:07:00,110 --> 00:07:00,690
Nonsense.

125
00:07:01,030 --> 00:07:01,990
Me and a sack?

126
00:07:02,390 --> 00:07:06,250
Flour flows into the fridge only in Pilsen and bats can hardly outdo lazy cockroaches.

127
00:07:12,050 --> 00:07:15,050
Bats can hardly outdo lazy cockroaches?

128
00:07:15,990 --> 00:07:17,470
Woman, you're babbling again.

129
00:07:17,850 --> 00:07:18,850
But...

130
00:07:19,050 --> 00:07:20,510
You were the one talking about bats first.

131
00:07:21,390 --> 00:07:22,990
Nonsense, I said there's nothing wrong with me.

132
00:07:23,070 --> 00:07:25,370
If you have ear problems, go to the doctor yourself.

133
00:07:25,610 --> 00:07:28,010
Excuse me, I've never had hearing problems.

134
00:07:28,170 --> 00:07:29,810
Must be those ear lanterns of yours.

135
00:07:30,130 --> 00:07:32,810
It's not dark in your ears for no reason, you know.

136
00:07:33,250 --> 00:07:36,450
And whoever turns on the light shouldn't be surprised to discover the lard of doom.

137
00:07:37,350 --> 00:07:38,350
And the tin gondola stirs up the salamis.

138
00:07:58,850 --> 00:08:02,750
The disease manifests first with mild, then increasingly marked disorientation.

139
00:08:12,250 --> 00:08:15,020
We've got a small problem.

140
00:08:15,020 --> 00:08:15,700
What is it?

141
00:08:16,350 --> 00:08:18,080
I'm getting disoriented.

142
00:08:18,750 --> 00:08:20,000
See, a clear symptom.

143
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:22,760
It's a clear symptom that you've been reading those books too long.

144
00:08:23,140 --> 00:08:25,520
Ivuska, what if I really do have the dysentery?

145
00:08:25,680 --> 00:08:26,340
Have you been to Africa?

146
00:08:26,540 --> 00:08:26,800
Well, no.

147
00:08:27,080 --> 00:08:28,140
Did you hug Benes?

148
00:08:28,850 --> 00:08:30,940
Did you hug Benes?

149
00:08:31,350 --> 00:08:32,220
What are you babbling about?

150
00:08:32,450 --> 00:08:32,950
See?

151
00:08:33,350 --> 00:08:35,350
Babbling, disorientation.

152
00:08:35,760 --> 00:08:37,100
Nigerian dysentery textbook case.

153
00:08:37,100 --> 00:08:44,050
Every time you read about diseases, you immediately have several fatal illnesses at once.

154
00:08:44,210 --> 00:08:47,310
Like when you got a rash from strawberries and thought you had shingles.

155
00:08:47,690 --> 00:08:49,030
Everyone's entitled to a mistake.

156
00:08:49,430 --> 00:08:52,310
Ivuska, I just feel that something's wrong.

157
00:08:52,590 --> 00:08:54,790
If you feel bad, go to the doctor.

158
00:08:54,930 --> 00:08:55,650
What good will that do?

159
00:08:55,710 --> 00:08:56,610
She'll just say there's nothing.

160
00:08:56,630 --> 00:08:58,470
Wrong with you, you're a hypochondriac, that'll be thirty crowns.

161
00:08:58,610 --> 00:08:59,930
Anyone can tell me that.

162
00:09:00,850 --> 00:09:04,590
See, there's nothing wrong with you, you're a hypochondriac, give me thirty crowns.

163
00:09:04,590 --> 00:09:05,510
Or better yet, a liter.

164
00:09:06,050 --> 00:09:07,350
I don't know how much the train will cost.

165
00:09:07,550 --> 00:09:09,350
But I'm not a hypochondriac!

166
00:09:09,350 --> 00:09:09,710
You are!

167
00:09:10,650 --> 00:09:17,350
Getting vaccinated for rabies when you bite your own tongue is perfectly normal.

168
00:09:18,050 --> 00:09:23,150
Fine, go then, but I hope you realize you might be seeing me for the last time.

169
00:09:23,160 --> 00:09:24,920
Dad, that's emotional blackmail.

170
00:09:24,920 --> 00:09:27,620
No, just go, I'll take care of myself.

171
00:09:28,050 --> 00:09:32,450
But I don't want to, that's why I turned on your phone and tell me the exact address where you're going.

172
00:09:33,350 --> 00:09:37,150
So that means ten texts before I get there.

173
00:09:37,250 --> 00:09:42,650
Ten calls during the night and in the morning you'll send Ozzak to bring me to your deathbed.

174
00:09:42,960 --> 00:09:44,580
Only if necessary.

175
00:09:45,240 --> 00:09:45,800
Great.

176
00:09:49,250 --> 00:09:50,350
So I'm not going anywhere.

177
00:09:51,250 --> 00:09:54,720
That's sweet of you to understand the seriousness of the situation.

178
00:09:54,720 --> 00:09:56,180
Ozzak at a class party.

179
00:09:56,450 --> 00:09:57,550
That would be serious.

180
00:10:05,280 --> 00:10:06,440
Hurry up, sis!

181
00:10:06,660 --> 00:10:08,060
It's terrible how slow you are.

182
00:10:08,180 --> 00:10:08,600
What's wrong with him?

183
00:10:09,250 --> 00:10:14,160
Horackova texted him that Novacek already drank two cartons of juice and will probably throw up soon.

184
00:10:14,160 --> 00:10:14,460
So what?

185
00:10:15,150 --> 00:10:17,760
I always used to be the first one to puke at every party.

186
00:10:17,760 --> 00:10:19,740
And everyone talked about me for two weeks after.

187
00:10:20,150 --> 00:10:23,260
If sis didn't take so long packing, we could've been there ages ago.

188
00:10:23,260 --> 00:10:24,800
I was packing important things.

189
00:10:26,550 --> 00:10:29,560
Map, toothbrush, sunscreen, what's important about that?

190
00:10:29,560 --> 00:10:31,000
And what important things did you pack?

191
00:10:33,020 --> 00:10:34,720
Vodka, Fernet, rum, and absinthe.

192
00:10:35,220 --> 00:10:37,100
And that's everything you're bringing?

193
00:10:37,380 --> 00:10:38,180
Of course not.

194
00:10:38,340 --> 00:10:39,120
Also a corkscrew.

195
00:10:45,350 --> 00:10:45,790
Great.

196
00:10:46,290 --> 00:10:47,310
Thanks a lot, sis.

197
00:10:48,650 --> 00:10:51,930
If we hurry, I can still be second.

198
00:10:52,050 --> 00:10:54,050
It's not about speed, it's about quality.

199
00:10:54,290 --> 00:10:55,530
Have fun.

200
00:10:55,570 --> 00:10:56,270
I'm not going.

201
00:10:56,750 --> 00:10:57,290
How come?

202
00:10:57,950 --> 00:11:00,050
Dad's sick, I have to take care of him.

203
00:11:00,400 --> 00:11:01,880
Then I'm not going either.

204
00:11:01,920 --> 00:11:03,000
What would I do there alone?

205
00:11:03,560 --> 00:11:04,460
Wait, what do you mean alone?

206
00:11:04,640 --> 00:11:05,860
Your whole class is going.

207
00:11:06,120 --> 00:11:08,160
Exactly, what would I do there alone with them?

208
00:11:08,420 --> 00:11:09,620
You've got to be kidding.

209
00:11:10,550 --> 00:11:14,520
You guys stay here and I'll end up at midnight in Luhacovice.

210
00:11:14,520 --> 00:11:16,820
Lexa, Luhacovice is in the completely opposite direction.

211
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:17,720
Exactly.

212
00:11:18,300 --> 00:11:19,400
Thanks a lot.

213
00:11:20,050 --> 00:11:21,350
I'm not going anywhere.

214
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:29,560
Ivuska!

215
00:11:30,980 --> 00:11:35,780
Hey, could you please be nice and make me that tea grandma used to make?

216
00:11:35,780 --> 00:11:44,720
When you caught a cold in winter, fever you've got, fighting with cramps, on top of it tea that heals, a drop of rum, a spoon of honey, won't let you go to heaven.

217
00:11:44,720 --> 00:11:45,460
Exactly.

218
00:11:47,250 --> 00:11:49,950
And most importantly, don't forget to put everything in that belongs.

219
00:11:53,150 --> 00:11:55,930
Wait, that was fast, you couldn't have had time to make it.

220
00:11:56,090 --> 00:11:59,010
I made it half an hour ago, but you couldn't be bothered to come get it.

221
00:11:59,190 --> 00:12:01,570
I'm disoriented, I might not manage it.

222
00:12:03,650 --> 00:12:07,950
Oh, but you didn't put ginger in it.

223
00:12:09,650 --> 00:12:13,050
Don't forget to always add fresh ginger root.

224
00:12:20,650 --> 00:12:24,450
She probably didn't slice the ginger.

225
00:12:24,750 --> 00:12:27,560
Sliced, grated ginger, same thing.

226
00:12:27,850 --> 00:12:31,150
Don't even think of using a grater for ginger.

227
00:12:40,750 --> 00:12:43,040
Ivuska, could you warm it up a little...

228
00:12:43,040 --> 00:12:44,060
Of course.

229
00:12:50,840 --> 00:12:51,960
Ouch, that burns.

230
00:12:53,000 --> 00:12:54,100
We need to cool it down.

231
00:13:02,350 --> 00:13:03,300
What are you doing?

232
00:13:03,300 --> 00:13:04,900
There's no verse about ice.

233
00:13:05,220 --> 00:13:06,360
Maybe she just didn't preserve it.

234
00:13:06,940 --> 00:13:09,720
Ivuska, I can't drink tea with ice when I have a temperature.

235
00:13:10,950 --> 00:13:11,520
You don't.

236
00:13:11,520 --> 00:13:11,840
What?

237
00:13:11,960 --> 00:13:12,400
I do.

238
00:13:12,850 --> 00:13:13,550
Wait.

239
00:13:14,050 --> 00:13:16,850
Here, feel, I've got this localized fever right here.

240
00:13:18,050 --> 00:13:22,140
You have no fever, no diarrhea, no thirst, and you're not disoriented.

241
00:13:22,140 --> 00:13:24,420
I happen to be disoriented like crazy.

242
00:13:24,560 --> 00:13:24,720
Yeah?

243
00:13:25,450 --> 00:13:26,980
Then show me how disoriented you are.

244
00:13:27,350 --> 00:13:28,150
Come on, I'm seriously sick, I'm not going to prove how sick I am when I'm sick.

245
00:13:32,680 --> 00:13:37,800
Fine, find someone who'll believe you're sick, who won't grate ginger on a grater, and who'll take care of you.

246
00:13:37,980 --> 00:13:39,020
I'm going to the cabin.

247
00:13:39,850 --> 00:13:43,350
Forgive in autumn, kindly be warming up.

248
00:13:52,250 --> 00:13:54,150
Ivuska, just go, I'll take care of bro.

249
00:13:54,450 --> 00:13:56,150
What, you taking care of Ozzak?

250
00:13:56,350 --> 00:13:57,850
You doubting me, bro?

251
00:13:58,050 --> 00:14:01,680
I used to push you to the swimming pool on a wooden cart when we were kids.

252
00:14:01,850 --> 00:14:04,400
Yeah, but you rarely brought me back.

253
00:14:04,400 --> 00:14:05,680
And who taught you to draw?

254
00:14:06,050 --> 00:14:11,500
You did, but when I drew it in first grade in the teacher's memory book, I got a bad mark in conduct.

255
00:14:11,500 --> 00:14:12,880
And who gave you your first guitar?

256
00:14:13,650 --> 00:14:17,680
Ozzak, but when the owner came for it, I lost two teeth.

257
00:14:17,680 --> 00:14:18,040
Very kind.

258
00:14:19,130 --> 00:14:20,710
You'll manage here just fine.

259
00:14:20,930 --> 00:14:21,230
What?

260
00:14:29,040 --> 00:14:30,320
Sasa, can we go?

261
00:14:30,520 --> 00:14:31,860
Iva, disaster.

262
00:14:32,060 --> 00:14:33,360
Lexa drank the booze stash.

263
00:14:50,800 --> 00:14:53,460
Lexa, good thing you're here, please.

264
00:14:53,720 --> 00:14:55,980
Can you help me light this ear candle?

265
00:14:56,020 --> 00:14:58,240
I feel like I'm having hearing problems.

266
00:15:03,950 --> 00:15:06,650
Mr. Ozzak was right, I really do have bad hearing.

267
00:15:07,350 --> 00:15:09,150
Lexa, do you understand what I'm saying?

268
00:15:12,550 --> 00:15:13,540
So that's how it is.

269
00:15:13,850 --> 00:15:18,550
Whatever, I'll get my things, close up here and make a doctor's appointment.

270
00:15:27,950 --> 00:15:29,750
Bro, there you are.

271
00:15:37,370 --> 00:15:38,930
Don't worry, your mom will sort that tea out.

272
00:15:47,750 --> 00:15:49,550
Bro, I'm feeling a bit faint.

273
00:15:49,950 --> 00:15:50,750
Weakling.

274
00:15:53,150 --> 00:15:54,750
I'm faint probably from hunger.

275
00:15:55,050 --> 00:15:55,850
Want a roll?

276
00:15:56,850 --> 00:16:00,190
When we were kids, Mom used to make garlic soup.

277
00:16:00,190 --> 00:16:00,890
With rolls.

278
00:16:02,450 --> 00:16:04,520
With soaked rolls?

279
00:16:05,150 --> 00:16:06,640
With soggy ones?

280
00:16:07,650 --> 00:16:09,050
So do you want the roll or not?

281
00:16:09,440 --> 00:16:10,140
Yeah.

282
00:16:20,350 --> 00:16:21,150
No rolls left.

283
00:16:23,550 --> 00:16:24,650
You'll get a cucumber.

284
00:16:30,350 --> 00:16:33,840
Look, Ozzak, I hope you don't expect me to eat this.

285
00:16:33,840 --> 00:16:34,340
You know what?

286
00:16:36,250 --> 00:16:38,650
No, it's just to entertain you.

287
00:16:39,050 --> 00:16:40,450
Cheer you up a bit.

288
00:16:40,800 --> 00:16:41,240
Combine harvester.

289
00:16:42,350 --> 00:16:46,530
Look, bro, I'm really feeling truly awful for this kind of humor.

290
00:16:46,850 --> 00:16:51,050
Try that on me one more time and I'll stuff your coat with buckshot till the frogs are hopping.

291
00:17:01,850 --> 00:17:03,960
Look, bro, you're testing how much I can take, right?

292
00:17:04,350 --> 00:17:07,900
You just want me to get up and walk over there myself.

293
00:17:07,950 --> 00:17:09,850
Tomas, you sly dog, you can't fool me.

294
00:17:13,250 --> 00:17:14,650
I think I'll go lie down.

295
00:17:18,050 --> 00:17:18,850
I can't do it.

296
00:17:19,580 --> 00:17:21,180
I can't even make it to the room.

297
00:17:21,460 --> 00:17:23,960
I don't even know which direction to go.

298
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:25,800
I'm completely disoriented.

299
00:17:26,550 --> 00:17:27,560
Easy, bro.

300
00:17:28,050 --> 00:17:28,900
I'll help you.

301
00:17:28,900 --> 00:17:35,660
Here we are.

302
00:17:44,450 --> 00:17:45,370
So what about vacation?

303
00:17:45,650 --> 00:17:46,950
Going anywhere this year?

304
00:17:47,350 --> 00:17:50,650
Around Europe or somewhere farther?

305
00:17:52,790 --> 00:17:53,390
Greece?

306
00:17:53,650 --> 00:17:55,670
I'm jealous, it's beautiful there.

307
00:17:55,810 --> 00:17:56,550
Who are you going with?

308
00:17:56,610 --> 00:17:57,190
Your wife?

309
00:18:01,250 --> 00:18:02,170
You puked on the waiter.

310
00:18:06,890 --> 00:18:10,510
Well, if all that happened to you, be glad you're going anywhere at all.

311
00:18:20,680 --> 00:18:21,700
You have to go to the hospital?

312
00:18:22,780 --> 00:18:24,000
You have a patient?

313
00:18:24,450 --> 00:18:25,740
This late?

314
00:18:25,740 --> 00:18:27,040
You never rest.

315
00:18:27,660 --> 00:18:28,940
That's terrible.

316
00:18:29,390 --> 00:18:30,310
Where do you work anyway?

317
00:18:31,750 --> 00:18:33,530
What, laryngology?

318
00:18:36,340 --> 00:18:38,520
Oh, otorhinolaryngology.

319
00:18:39,060 --> 00:18:39,660
Right.

320
00:18:43,580 --> 00:18:44,180
What?

321
00:18:45,250 --> 00:18:46,530
I'll rip him apart.

322
00:18:46,950 --> 00:18:48,750
Yeah, I'm closing up and I'll be right there.

323
00:18:49,350 --> 00:18:50,650
You'll have to go.

324
00:18:50,950 --> 00:18:54,230
But my son got drunk and is bothering the neighbors.

325
00:18:54,230 --> 00:18:55,050
You'll have to.

326
00:18:55,930 --> 00:18:57,330
No, I'm not pouring you any more.

327
00:19:10,150 --> 00:19:10,630
Alright.

328
00:19:10,650 --> 00:19:12,190
Ozzak, what are you doing?

329
00:19:12,190 --> 00:19:13,430
You can't carry me.

330
00:19:13,750 --> 00:19:14,450
Come on.

331
00:19:14,950 --> 00:19:17,970
How many times did I bounce you on these shoulders, huh?

332
00:19:18,350 --> 00:19:20,030
That was thirty-five years ago.

333
00:19:20,030 --> 00:19:22,350
Don't you think things have changed since then?

334
00:19:22,450 --> 00:19:23,550
Like maybe I've grown?

335
00:19:23,730 --> 00:19:24,550
And I haven't?

336
00:19:25,050 --> 00:19:29,450
Where would I be if I couldn't carry my own little bro?

337
00:19:30,450 --> 00:19:31,250
All aboard.

338
00:19:33,350 --> 00:19:34,970
Three, two, one, go!

339
00:19:35,190 --> 00:19:36,430
And there you go!

340
00:19:37,550 --> 00:19:38,550
And giddyup!

341
00:19:39,280 --> 00:19:40,060
Where to?

342
00:19:40,950 --> 00:19:42,480
To the room, buddy.

343
00:19:42,480 --> 00:19:42,900
Right.

344
00:19:48,730 --> 00:19:49,390
What is it?

345
00:19:49,850 --> 00:19:51,770
Just carrying you around for a bit.

346
00:19:56,750 --> 00:20:01,350
Look, bro, I don't want to overwork you.

347
00:20:01,550 --> 00:20:02,890
I can see you need a break.

348
00:20:02,890 --> 00:20:03,990
Good idea.

349
00:20:04,050 --> 00:20:04,830
Let's take a breather.

350
00:20:05,470 --> 00:20:06,770
We're close to the couch, right?

351
00:20:06,810 --> 00:20:07,850
Yeah, come on, let's go.

352
00:20:12,950 --> 00:20:13,850
Phone.

353
00:20:14,350 --> 00:20:15,250
We can handle this.

354
00:20:15,590 --> 00:20:17,050
I'll put you down.

355
00:20:17,690 --> 00:20:18,810
Or I'll hold you by the legs.

356
00:20:36,750 --> 00:20:39,450
Tomas, I'm closing early today.

357
00:20:39,650 --> 00:20:41,750
I need to see a doctor.

358
00:20:42,650 --> 00:20:47,100
Tomas, I can't understand you at all, Tomas.

359
00:20:47,350 --> 00:20:47,950
Pardon, pardon.

360
00:20:53,150 --> 00:20:56,650
God, I can't even hear you.

361
00:20:57,050 --> 00:21:01,050
It's even worse than I thought.

362
00:21:11,750 --> 00:21:12,650
Lexa.

363
00:21:12,680 --> 00:21:13,880
Drink up, it'll do you good.

364
00:21:15,450 --> 00:21:20,440
I doubt Lexa intends to drink anything more.

365
00:21:20,440 --> 00:21:21,820
He must be soaked like a sponge.

366
00:21:26,680 --> 00:21:28,880
A camel, also known as the minibus of our forests.

367
00:21:31,140 --> 00:21:33,040
I was supposed to be at the cabin.

368
00:21:33,040 --> 00:21:40,250
I was supposed to be dreamily watching Hajek play an out-of-tune guitar, Horackova braiding flowers in her hair, and Novacek throwing up.

369
00:21:44,730 --> 00:21:47,390
Iva, don't talk about Novacek in front of him, look how upset he got.

370
00:21:49,150 --> 00:21:51,450
Caramel is a concrete dog.

371
00:21:52,050 --> 00:21:53,250
So, what's going on here?

372
00:21:58,050 --> 00:21:59,750
What do you know about what he's thinking, kid?

373
00:22:02,630 --> 00:22:04,150
You only drank a tiny bit, right?

374
00:22:04,790 --> 00:22:05,910
Look at yourself.

375
00:22:06,010 --> 00:22:07,310
Why did you get so wrecked, for God's sake?

376
00:22:10,150 --> 00:22:13,050
Right, so when Novacek jumps out the window, you'll jump after him?

377
00:22:13,110 --> 00:22:13,630
I don't know.

378
00:22:13,810 --> 00:22:14,430
Before him?

379
00:22:14,650 --> 00:22:14,990
I don't know.

380
00:22:15,470 --> 00:22:16,690
Whose kid are you?

381
00:22:17,330 --> 00:22:17,850
Mom's.

382
00:22:18,890 --> 00:22:20,010
Who poured for you, I know that much.

383
00:22:20,910 --> 00:22:22,390
A weathervane can hardly hit the bottom.

384
00:22:23,330 --> 00:22:24,530
And what did this one drink?

385
00:22:24,530 --> 00:22:26,230
You can't understand a word he says.

386
00:22:26,230 --> 00:22:28,170
We don't know, he was already lying here like this.

387
00:22:28,290 --> 00:22:29,390
Something might be wrong with him.

388
00:22:32,350 --> 00:22:33,400
Ozzak has a fever.

389
00:22:33,400 --> 00:22:34,580
40.2.

390
00:22:34,780 --> 00:22:35,640
That's nonsense.

391
00:22:36,250 --> 00:22:37,050
You're right.

392
00:22:37,490 --> 00:22:38,410
40.3.

393
00:22:39,330 --> 00:22:39,790
Nonsense!

394
00:22:39,790 --> 00:22:44,850
The only seriously sick person in this room is me, but nobody here gives a damn.

395
00:22:45,150 --> 00:22:47,750
Tomas, I can tell when someone's dying.

396
00:22:48,750 --> 00:22:49,350
What?

397
00:22:51,250 --> 00:22:55,450
Okay, it's not that serious, but you should definitely rush him to the hospital.

398
00:23:00,050 --> 00:23:01,250
Let's go, kid.

399
00:23:01,950 --> 00:23:08,350
Look, I can assure you, you'll get your butt kicked sooner than Novacek.

400
00:23:10,250 --> 00:23:12,250
See how easy it is, bro.

401
00:23:12,470 --> 00:23:13,950
You're light as a feather.

402
00:23:26,050 --> 00:23:28,260
Novakova from the fifth floor is badmouthing Ozzak again.

403
00:23:28,650 --> 00:23:31,150
Says he doesn't wash, so no wonder he ended up in the hospital.

404
00:23:31,450 --> 00:23:36,860
Marcelka, did the doctor really say you need a hearing aid?

405
00:23:36,860 --> 00:23:37,860
What did the doctor say?

406
00:23:37,960 --> 00:23:39,100
I didn't understand him.

407
00:23:39,100 --> 00:23:42,000
And what do you do when you can't understand your ENT doctor?

408
00:23:42,250 --> 00:23:43,520
You buy a hearing aid.

409
00:23:43,520 --> 00:23:44,980
Now I hear better than ever.

410
00:23:45,220 --> 00:23:46,140
Hey, hey!

411
00:23:46,950 --> 00:23:49,550
Mrs. Podehnalov from the fifth floor is also talking about Ozzak.

412
00:23:49,550 --> 00:23:51,070
Yeah, the whole building's talking about him.

413
00:23:51,210 --> 00:23:52,030
The whole building?

414
00:23:52,130 --> 00:23:53,630
The whole street's talking about him.

415
00:23:54,650 --> 00:23:56,330
I'm surprised how much everyone misses him.

416
00:23:56,450 --> 00:23:59,450
Four people came to the store today asking about him.

417
00:23:59,650 --> 00:24:06,950
And when I told them he's being released from the hospital today, they were so happy they didn't even steal anything.

418
00:24:07,450 --> 00:24:09,390
How did the delivery go?

419
00:24:09,390 --> 00:24:10,110
Smoothly, Dad.

420
00:24:10,290 --> 00:24:12,710
Lexa and the driver brought the fruit right to his room.

421
00:24:12,830 --> 00:24:13,110
What?

422
00:24:13,230 --> 00:24:16,070
We clearly agreed that visits are forbidden.

423
00:24:16,950 --> 00:24:20,470
Ozzak couldn't bear knowing that we know he's in the hospital.

424
00:24:20,470 --> 00:24:21,150
Did he recognize you?

425
00:24:21,270 --> 00:24:21,390
No.

426
00:24:21,830 --> 00:24:24,430
I was disguised as a nurse and Sasa as a patient.

427
00:24:24,590 --> 00:24:25,350
It was great.

428
00:24:25,650 --> 00:24:27,650
Mr. Ozzak was very happy about the fruit.

429
00:24:27,730 --> 00:24:29,510
He even has a special bed for it.

430
00:24:30,190 --> 00:24:32,050
He's probably waiting for it to ferment.

431
00:24:32,390 --> 00:24:33,510
He looks much better already.

432
00:24:33,570 --> 00:24:35,110
He slapped my butt twice.

433
00:24:35,150 --> 00:24:37,790
And the beer I left on the nightstand was gone in no time.

434
00:24:38,350 --> 00:24:39,550
He's getting back to normal.

435
00:24:43,250 --> 00:24:45,550
Benes writes that they released him.

436
00:24:45,950 --> 00:24:47,070
False alarm.

437
00:24:47,550 --> 00:24:49,450
Oh, so there might be school tomorrow.

438
00:24:51,650 --> 00:24:52,450
Well, actually...

439
00:24:52,850 --> 00:24:54,750
Unlikely.

440
00:24:57,450 --> 00:24:58,450
I can hear him already.

441
00:24:59,250 --> 00:25:00,950
He just opened the front door.

442
00:25:01,550 --> 00:25:03,280
Now he's opening the elevator door.

443
00:25:03,280 --> 00:25:04,770
And now he coughed.

444
00:25:05,510 --> 00:25:06,850
And here he is.

445
00:25:07,010 --> 00:25:09,650
Ozzak, I've got new hearing aids, now I'll understand you.

446
00:25:09,830 --> 00:25:10,650
That's good, bimbo.

447
00:25:10,930 --> 00:25:11,790
They always work.

448
00:25:12,190 --> 00:25:16,110
Ivuska, Tomas, you're looking good.

449
00:25:16,430 --> 00:25:18,170
I'm glad you're all right.

450
00:25:20,150 --> 00:25:21,650
Well then, all roads lead home.

451
00:25:22,150 --> 00:25:27,750
Not that I couldn't last in that hospital, but I didn't want to leave the store unsupervised for too long.

452
00:25:30,350 --> 00:25:33,310
Don't ask me anything, a real man has to keep some things to himself.

453
00:25:33,650 --> 00:25:39,650
But I picked these for you, so you'd have vitamins and wouldn't get sick.

454
00:25:41,850 --> 00:25:42,380
Cheers.

455
00:25:42,380 --> 00:25:53,800
Doctor, it's improved significantly since last time.

456
00:25:53,880 --> 00:25:55,800
I can understand everyone even without the hearing aid now.

457
00:25:56,000 --> 00:25:57,160
Well, we think.

458
00:25:57,550 --> 00:25:59,450
But we're above.

459
00:25:59,730 --> 00:26:00,390
Clearly obvious.

